JOHANNESBURG - British actress Emma Chambers, who achieved broad recognition by playing Hugh Grant's younger sister, Honey in the 1999 breakout hit Notting Hill, has died, aged 53. Chambers, who also performed alongside Dawn French in TV series The Vicar of Dibley, is believed to have suffered a heart attack and died on Wednesday evening. She is survived by her husband, Ian Dunn, a fellow actor. French, in a tweet, said, "I loved her. A lot". 'Notting Hill' actress Emma Chambers died at age 53 https://t.co/Ua3eDX9KHm pic.twitter.com/s73zg8s9ox Vicar of Dibley and Notting Hill star Emma Chambers died of ‘suspected heart attack’ https://t.co/Tq8RH4H6EI Emma Chambers, actress in The Vicar of Dibley and Notting Hill – obituary https://t.co/iUu9rfYEJg In memoriam Emma Chambers (1964-2018). pic.twitter.com/nw0yDXuquh Hugh Grant described his Notting Hill  co-star as a "hilarious and very warm person and of course a brilliant actress." Emma Chambers was a hilarious and very warm person and of course a brilliant actress. Very sad news. One of the funniest scenes ever, perfectly played by Dawn French and Emma Chambers. #EmmaChambers RIP pic.twitter.com/6L6dKy4iiS eNCA